<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[691,1220,340,1590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
COMMENTS: The family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1016,1113,1332,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nepidae</taxonomicName>
is composed of some 200 species and 12 genera around the world (
<bibRefCitation author="Menke, A. S." box="[908,1070,1391,1414]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 166" refId="ref11807" refString="Menke, A. S. 1979. The semiaquatic and aquatic Hemiptera of California (Heteroptera: Hemiptera). Bulletin of the California Insect Survey 21: 1 - 166." type="journal article" year="1979">Menke, 1979</bibRefCitation>
). This single specimen is, in our opinion, an unusual species, but one that clearly falls within the limits of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday. Six" authorityYear="1833" box="[897,983,1479,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Thoron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[897,983,1479,1502]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Thoron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Its disjunct distribution strongly suggests to us that there are more species yet to be discovered along calm watercourses in tropical Asia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
